# TDD & Review Loop

- For non-trivial logic changes, bug fixes, and behavior changes, default to test-first work.
- Write or update the smallest test that proves the expected behavior before implementing the change.
- Run the targeted test to confirm the failure is real and relevant, then implement the minimal fix.
- After the targeted test passes, run the broader verification needed for the touched area before claiming completion.
- Do not describe work as done unless you can separate: `changed in code`, `verified locally`, and `verified in runtime/deployed environment`.

## Iteration Discipline

- When work is broken into TODOs or phases, complete one slice, then stop and review before starting the next.
- The review pass must check: correctness, regressions, edge cases, naming/clarity, missing tests, and observability gaps.
- Fix important review findings before moving to the next TODO.
- If a review changes behavior, re-run verification before continuing.

## Anti-Slippage Rules

- Do not skip tests because the change looks small.
- Do not write a batch of code first and "add tests later."
- Do not move to the next step just because the code compiles.
- Do not claim a checklist item is met without evidence.
